                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4600: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="to"
                            >Wilson</persName>), at Geneva</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-08T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 8, 1932—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>35. Your 58, March 7, 2 p.m. I feel that in such conversations with
                    representatives of other states you should proceed guardedly as regards
                    initiative. In particular, you should guard against giving any impression that
                    the American Government is taking sides as between China and Japan. Our position
                    is based on our view of treaty rights and obligations, and we must not become
                    protagonists of the views, interests or activities, as such, of either of the
                        disputants.<note n="65" xml:id="d570fn65">The Minister replied in telegram
                        No. 66, March 9, 4 p.m.: “All members of the Delegation have made and will
                        continue to make the idea you lay down our guiding principle.”
                        (793.94/4641)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
